Problem 1: Manufacturing flaws in circuit boards

Part A

The boxplot is showing the correlation between opening size on a soldier gun and the number solder skips. In general, as the openings get smaller the number of skips also decreases, as the median decreases and the max value decreases (while keeping the min constant).

The boxplot is showing the correlation between whether the solder is thick or not, and the number of solder skips. In general, thick solders have a lower number of skips as shown by the lower median and the lower max (keeping the min relatively the same).

Part C

  • If the opening is large and the solder is thick, the expected solder skips is 0.393.
  • If the opening is medium and the solder is thick, the expected solder skips increases by 2.407.
  • If the opening is small and the solder is thick, the expected solder skips increases by 5.127.
  • If the opening is large and the solder is thin, the expected solder skips increases by 2.280
  • If the opening is large and the solder is thick, the expected solder skips decreases by .740
  • If the opening is medium and the solder is thin, the expected solder skips increases by 9.653.

Part D

If I had to recommend a combination of Opening size and Solder thicknes to AT&T based on the analysis, I would pick an opening that is large and the solder is thic, as that actually has the lowest expected number of skips.

Problem 2: Grocery store prices

Part A.

The bar plot shows the average product price by store. Whole Foods and Wheatsville Food Co-Op generally have high average prices, while stores like Walmart and Fiesta have low average prices. In generally these stores are known to offer more cheaper alternatives, while the more expensive stores offer more premium products.

Part B.

The bar plot shows the number of stores carrying each product. Lucky Charms and Frosted Flakes generally have lower counts, while products like 2% milk and eggs have high counts. In general, products like cereal that are less fresh, are not as popular as fresh products like eggs or milk.

Part C.

## # A tibble: 1 × 7
##   term          estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
##   <chr>            <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 Type: Grocery   -0.664     0.128     -5.20       0   -0.915   -0.413

With this lm model, we are keeping Convenience stores as the reference category, which means we can compare prices at other store types keeping the convenience store as a base. For groceries, the coefficient was -.664, while the confidence interval was (-.915, -.413). Grocery stores in general charge less than a dollar compared to convience stores for the same items.

Poorer ZIP codes do pay more for the same product as Income10k’s coefficient is less than zero implying that an increase in income, predicted price goes down for the same item. But because the p-value is quite big, and the confidence interval includes 0, there is not a statistically significant relationship. A one-standard deviation increase in the income of a ZIP code seems to be associated with a -0.0315971 standard deviation change in the price that consumers in that ZIP code expect to pay for the same product.

Problem 3: redlining

A. ZIP codes with a higher percentage of minority residents tend to have more FAIR policies per 100 housing units. - True, figure A1 displays a positive linear relationship between Minority and FAIR policies and model_A displays that minority has .014 as a coefficient, with a low p value (and confidence interval of .009 - .018).

B. The evidence suggests an interaction effect between minority percentage and the age of the housing stock in the way that these two variables are related to the number of FAIR policies in a ZIP code. - Undecidable, because none of the graphs display a relationship between minority and age. Something like the below code would answer the code: model_interaction <- lm(policies ~ minority * age, data = redlining) library(moderndive) get_regression_table(model_interaction) I would look at the term labeled minority:age.

C. The relationship between minority percentage and number of FAIR policies per 100 housing units is stronger in high-fire-risk ZIP codes than in low-fire-risk ZIP codes. - True, figure C1 displays that the slope for the low fire risk line is lower than high fire risk’s line. In addition, model_C has a coefficient of .01 and a p-value of .015 which is a very low p-value showing that the relationship between minority percentage and number of FAIR policies per 100 housing units is stronger in high-fire-risk ZIP codes.

D. Even without controlling for any other variables, income “explains away” all the association between minority percentage and FAIR policy uptake. - False, even after controlling for income, minority percentage remains associated with FAIR policy uptake. model_D2 displays that minority has a low p-value and singificant coefficient despite income being included. The effect is somewhat diminished compared to model_D1, but it remains significant.

E. Minority percentage and number of FAIR policies are still associated at the ZIP code level, even after controlling for income, fire risk, and housing age. - True, model_E has minority, income, fire risk, and housing age. The coefficient in minority is positive and has a low p-value. Confidence interval is also positive.
